  "text": "Kafka broker SASL mechanism configuration validation occurs across multiple layers during broker startup:\n\n## sasl.enabled.mechanisms Validation\n\nThe primary validation happens in `KafkaConfig.scala` in the `validateValues()` method (line 502-651). At line 628-629, it validates that when SASL is used for inter-broker communication, the configured `SASL_MECHANISM_INTER_BROKER_PROTOCOL_CONFIG` must be included in the `SASL_ENABLED_MECHANISMS_CONFIG` list. The configuration definitions are specified in `BrokerSecurityConfigs.java` (lines 97-101) which defines `SASL_ENABLED_MECHANISMS_CONFIG` as the list of SASL mechanisms enabled in the Kafka server.\n\n## JAAS Configuration Validation\n\nJAAS configuration validation happens in `JaasContext.java` through the `loadServerContext()` method (line 65-75). This method:\n1. Validates that both listenerName and mechanism are provided (lines 66-69)\n2. Loads the dynamic JAAS config from the property with format: `mechanism.lowercase.sasl.jaas.config`\n3. Calls the `load()` method (line 90-104) which validates:\n   - That the JAAS config contains exactly one login module (lines 95-98)\n   - That the login module is allowed via `throwIfLoginModuleIsNotAllowed()` (line 100)\n\nThe JAAS configuration parsing and validation is further handled by `JaasConfig.java` which parses the JAAS configuration string and validates:\n- The login module is specified (line 66)\n- The login module control flag is valid (line 85-104)\n- Configuration entries are properly terminated by semicolons (line 121)\n\n## Channel Builder Configuration\n\nAt broker startup, `ChannelBuilders.java` in the `serverChannelBuilder()` method (line 96-108) and the `create()` method (line 135-141) iterate through all enabled SASL mechanisms from `BrokerSecurityConfigs.SASL_ENABLED_MECHANISMS_CONFIG` and load a `JaasContext` for each mechanism via `JaasContext.loadServerContext()`.\n\n## Mechanism-Specific Configuration Validation\n\n### SCRAM Validation\n`ScramServerCallbackHandler.java` (line 48) has a `configure()` method that sets up SCRAM-specific configuration when SCRAM mechanisms are enabled.\n\n### OAUTHBEARER Validation\n`OAuthBearerUnsecuredValidatorCallbackHandler.java` validates OAUTHBEARER configuration in its `configure()` method (line 114-122):\n- Checks that the SASL mechanism is OAUTHBEARER (line 116)\n- Validates that exactly one JAAS configuration entry exists (line 117-118)\n- Sets `configured` flag to true once successfully configured (line 123)\n\n### GSSAPI/Kerberos Validation\n`KerberosClientCallbackHandler.java` validates GSSAPI configuration in its `configure()` method (line 39-41):\n- Throws an exception if GSSAPI mechanism is not GSSAPI (line 41)\n\n## Dynamic Configuration\n`DynamicBrokerConfig.scala` identifies SASL-related configs as dynamically reconfigurable (lines 902-914), managing updates to `SASL_MECHANISM_INTER_BROKER_PROTOCOL_CONFIG`, `SASL_JAAS_CONFIG`, and `SASL_ENABLED_MECHANISMS_CONFIG`.\n\n## Configuration Definitions\n`SaslConfigs.java` defines all SASL configuration properties including documentation for `SASL_JAAS_CONFIG` (lines 35-40) which specifies the required format for broker configurations with listener prefix and mechanism name in lowercase.\n\nThe validation ensures that: (1) enabled mechanisms are properly configured with JAAS entries, (2) inter-broker protocol uses an enabled mechanism, (3) JAAS configuration strings are properly formatted with exactly one login module, and (4) mechanism-specific validators can successfully initialize their configurations."
